main event: A radar intercept of an unidentified high-speed object over Custer AF Sta., Michigan on July 12, 1956.
interesting points: The radar operator who tracked the object was described as 'very reliable'.
The object made 5 passes at varied speeds and faded in and out of the radar screen.
The preliminary analysis indicated this was a 'positive indication that this was actually a high speed object tracked'.
The document states there was 'insufficient data for evaluation' and 'no action is being taken pending receipt of additional information'.
The sighting was reported to various military commands, including the Air Defense Command, Director of Intelligence, and the 75th Acuron at Custer AF Sta.
sighted object: unidentified high-speed object tracked on radar
